{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517457"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12806"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12806"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.13,0.02,0.03,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109676"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5247"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92079"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44537"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109676"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a one day history of severe and constant generalised abdominal pain. She could not identify any triggers for her pain. She is experiencing nausea without vomiting. She does not have any other symptoms. Her history includes atrial fibrillation, congestive heart failure, type 2 diabetes mellitus and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Her regular medications are enalapril, metoprolol, warfarin, furosemide, spironolactone and insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is afebrile. Her pulse is 70/min, irregular, and her blood pressure is 135/85 mmHg. She has diffuse abdominal tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory studies show the following results (with reference ranges):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin (Hb): 100 g/L (120-150)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite blood cell (WBC) count: 17.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium (Na): 144 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride (Cl): 105 mmol/L (98-107)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium (K): 4.0 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate (HCO3): 20 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine (Cr): 97 \u00b5mol/L (53-97)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlycated haemoglobin (HbA1c): 12.6% (4.0-6.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternational normalized ratio (INR): 1.6 (0.9-1.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography (CT) angiography","Abdominal X-ray","Colonoscopy","Endoscopy","Serum amylase and lipase"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most important condition to exclude in this patient is mesenteric ischaemia. Pain out of proportion to the clinical examination findings is very suggestive of this diagnosis. Apart from the current clinical picture, she has atherosclerotic risk factors as well as atrial fibrillation and these all support a diagnosis of mesenteric ischaemia. Despite being on warfarin her INR is currently subtherapeutic as in atrial fibrillation (without a mechanical valve) the target INR would be between 2-3.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith this likely condition in mind, \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most helpful investigation to confirm the diagnosis. CT angiography has high sensitivity and specificity in the setting of acute mesenteric ischaemia and can help diagnose this condition by showing evidence of arterial occlusion, bowel wall thickening, or pneumatosis intestinalis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E abdominal X-ray \u003C/strong\u003Ecan provide information about the presence of bowel obstruction, bowel perforation, or other abnormalities in the abdomen. However, it does not provide detailed visualisation of the abdominal structures and vasculature. It could show evidence of pneumatosis intestinalis, thumb printing and portal vein gas, but these are all late findings. Given the severity of the patient\u0027s symptoms and the need for urgent evaluation, a more comprehensive imaging study like CT angiography would be the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopy and colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would help evaluate for many causes of abdominal pain but will delay the time to diagnosis of mesenteric ischaemia, which is needed urgently to prevent infarction/necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum amylase and lipase\u003C/strong\u003E might be appropriate if the patient was thought to have pancreatitis, but this is outweighed by the clinical picture adding up to mesenteric ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Computed tomography angiography (CT-A) should be performed without delay in any patient with suspicion for acute mesenteric ischaemia."],"references":["Bala, M., Catena, F., Kashuk, J. et al. Acute mesenteric ischemia: updated guidelines of the World Society of Emergency Surgery. World J Emerg Surg 17, 54 (2022). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13017-022-00443-x","Monita MM, Gonzalez L. Acute Mesenteric Ischemia. [Updated 2022 Jun 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92079"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92079"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-24T16:58:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T16:59:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5247"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109676"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici